user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following OS_TaskDetach_Impl code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 8.13.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 is A pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible.

</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of OS_TaskDetach_Impl.
```c
int32 OS_TaskDetach_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    OS_impl_task_internal_record_t *impl;
    int                             ret;

    impl = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_impl_task_table, *token);

    ret = pthread_detach(impl->id);

    if (ret != 0)
    {
        OS_DEBUG("pthread_detach: Failed on Task ID = %lu, err = %s\n",
                 OS_ObjectIdToInteger(OS_ObjectIdFromToken(token)), strerror(ret));
        return OS_ERROR;
    }

    return OS_SUCCESS;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
In OS_TaskDetach_Impl the expression OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_impl_task_table, *token) produces an OS_impl_task_internal_record_t * pointing at an element of OS_impl_task_table, and the local variable 'impl' is declared as a non-const pointer even though it is only used for read access (impl->id). Per MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 the pointer should be to a const-qualified type (e.g. const OS_impl_task_internal_record_t *impl) when modification is not required.
</scenario>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are close to the target function OS_TaskDetach_Impl:
typedef struct OS_object_token OS_object_token_t
...
typedef struct
{
    pthread_t id;
} OS_impl_task_internal_record_t
...
OS_impl_task_internal_record_t OS_impl_task_table[OS_MAX_TASKS]
...
#define OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(tbl, tok) (&tbl[OS_ObjectIndexFromToken(&(tok))])
...
static inline osal_id_t OS_ObjectIdFromToken(const OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    return token->obj_id;
}
...
